0.1 Linear Classifier

How to classify various data points into two types ( for example : spam/non spam emails):

How to identify equation of a classifier (straight line in 2D plane) which can split this data sets in two groups?

A quick detour with Vector Algebra :

Let’s assume the plane P is the hyperplane which will be used to classify two groups of data. x is any vector. Distance between point x and the hyperplane is given by \alpha\theta. Why? Theta is the Perpendicular to the plane. So the vector to point x is given by \alpha\theta

We need to find this \alpha\theta. By vector geometry :

w+z=x

Equation of the plane is given by \theta.x=0 where x is given by:

x= \begin{bmatrix} x_1 \\ x_2 \\ x_3 \\ ....\\ x_n \end{bmatrix} \tag{0}

z=x-w \tag{1} \theta^T.z = \theta^T.x-\theta^T.w \tag{2} z= $$

NotePseudocode

Update theta once the distance calculated is less than 0.

def perceptron_single_step_update( feature_vector, label, current_theta, current_theta_0): 
rows = feature_vector.shape[0]
decision = label*(np.dot(current_theta, feature_vector)+current_theta_0)

if decision <= 0:
    current_theta = current_theta + label*feature_vector
    current_theta_0 = current_theta_0 + label
    return (current_theta, current_theta_0)
else:
    return (current_theta, current_theta_0)


def perceptron(feature_matrix, labels, T):
    theta = np.zeros(feature_matrix.shape[1])
    theta_0 = 0
    nsamples = feature_matrix.shape[0]
    
    for t in range(T):
        for i in get_order(nsamples):
            # Your code here
            theta, theta_0 = perceptron_single_step_update(
                feature_matrix[i], labels[i], theta, theta_0)
            # print("current theta",theta)
    return (theta, theta_0)

0.3 Large Margin Classifier

The decision boundary equation is given by:

\theta^T.x +\theta_0 = 0 \tag{4}

The two margins are given by :

\theta^T.x +\theta_0 = -1 \tag{5}

\theta^T.x +\theta_0 = +1 \tag{6}

The distance between this two margins are given by :

D=\frac{2}{\theta}\tag {7}

Implications of the margin : larger the margin the better is the

0.3.1 Underfitting vs Overfitting:

During Training all images are not perfectly classified.

0.4 Optimizing Perceptron :

What makes a classifier good classifier: When its able to split into two groups properly. That means for a proper classified group we can have an wide margin. How do we make it a wide margin? by changing the parameter. We can change the magnitude of theta to change the width of the margin:

Let’s create a new theta by dividing the current theta:

\theta^{'}=\theta/c

from 4:

\theta^T.x +\theta_0 = 0 \tag{4}

Dividing both sides by c

\frac{\theta^T.x}{c} +\frac{\theta_0}{c} = 0 \tag{5}

\theta^{'T}.x +\theta_0^{'} = 0\tag{6}

The equation of the classifier is still valid. For the margin equations:

\theta^{'T}.x +\theta_0{'} = \frac{-1}{c} \tag{7}

\theta^{'T}.x +\theta_0^{'} = \frac{1}{c} \tag{8}

Distance between these two lines is

d'=\frac{2c}{\theta} \approx \frac{\lambda}{\theta}\tag{9}

0.4.1 Regularisation

The goal is to regulate the model. This creates a wide margin and underfitting. We can increase the margin by regulating \lambda

The distance on one side is \frac{1}{||\theta||}. The distance is maximized at \frac{1}{||\theta||^2}

0.4.2 Loss Function:

This is the Loss when the model is over fitted during training and then it misses classification points during testing.How is this loss function calculated. we will penalize the model by assigning a loss value ( a number) so that we can nudge towards our intended solution.

Loss_h = g(y_{i}*(\theta.x_i))\tag{10}

= \begin{cases} 1 & \text{if } z>1 \\ 1-z & \text{if } z<=1 \\ \end{cases}\tag{11}

0.4.3 Optimizing Function

J=Loss_h + \frac{1}{||\theta||^2} \tag{12}

J=\sum_1^n g(y_i(\theta.x_i)) + \frac{1}{||\theta||^2} \tag{13}

J=\frac{1}{n}\sum_1^n g(y_i(\theta.x_i+\theta_0)) + \frac{1}{||\theta||^2} \tag{14}

J= Average Loss + Regularization
